In this Play, as in the Adelphi‚ the division of Acts and Scenes in the MSS. is dramatically impossible, and is doubtless due to a copyist's ignorance. This edition adopts the arrangement found in practice to be the most natural and convenient, but the old numbering os Acts and Scenes is preserved in brackets for purposes of reference.

Demipho is boiling over with rage at his son’s unauthon‘sed and imprudent marriage. Phaedria loyally defends his cousin, and assisted by Geta makes every possible excuse. Between them they manage to divert the old man’s wrath upon Phormio's head.
